'''Peter John Michael Clarke''', [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order|CVO]], [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Queen's Police Medal|QPM]] (born 27 July 1955) is a retired senior police officer with [[London]]'s [[Metropolitan Police]] most notably having served as a [[Deputy Assistant Commissioner]] with the [[Specialist Operations]] directorate, commanding the [[Counter Terrorism Command]].<ref name="Guardian I">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2005/jul/29/july7.duncancampbell|title=The Guardian profile: Peter Clarke|author=Campbell, Duncan; Cowan, Rosie|date=29 July 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>

==Early and personal life==
Clarke was educated at the [[Glyn School]], [[Epsom]] and holds a [[LL.B|degree in law]] and an Honorary Doctorate in Law from the [[University of Bristol]].  He is married with three children. He lists [[cricket]] and [[Rugby football|rugby]] among his interests.<ref name="Guardian I"/>

==Career==
Clarke joined the [[Metropolitan Police]] in 1977, progressing through the ranks to reach [[Inspector#United Kingdom|inspector]] in 1984, becoming a detective inspector in 1986 before joining the National Drugs Intelligence Unit in 1988. Subsequently promoted, Clarke became Operations Chief, Central London division in 1990 and staff officer to the [[commissioner of Police of the Metropolis|Met commissioner]] in 1993 followed by three years as divisional commander, [[Brixton]] from 1994 to 1997.<ref name="Guardian I"/> 

Clarke then spent a further 3 years as a [[Commander#British police rank|Commander]], heading the [[Protection Command]] between 1997 and 2000, a role which placed him in charge of [[Protection Command#Royalty Protection|Royalty protection]] at the time of the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]],<ref name="Guardian II">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2007/jul/03/terrorism.world4|title=Tough task for chief with gentle touch|date=3 July 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref> followed by 2 years as deputy director of personnel from 2000 to 2002. In June 2002, Clarke became head of the [[Metropolitan Police Anti Terrorism Branch|Anti-terrorist Branch]], later merged with [[Special Branch#United Kingdom|Special Branch]] to form the [[Counter Terrorist Command]], a role which put him in direct control of the investigation into the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|7 July attacks]] on London and the [[21 July 2005 London bombings|failed bomb attempts]] of 21 July 2005.<ref name="Guardian I"/>

Clarke retired as Assistant Commissioner Specialist Operations in February 2008, having delayed his retirement at the request of the then [[Commissioner]], [[Sir Ian Blair]], following the resignation of [[Andy Hayman]].<ref name="Telegraph I">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/2066861/Terror-law-should-allow-42-days-detention-says-former-police-chief-Peter-Clarke.html|title=Terror law should allow 42 days' detention, says former police chief Peter Clarke|last=Porter|first=Andrew|date=2 June 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref>

==Later life==
Clarke has been vocal in his retirement in campaigning for tougher legislation on terrorism.  More controversially this has including extended detention before charge for terrorist suspects, giving examples of where it has sometimes proven necessary to make arrests at an early stage in inquiries to protect the public sufficiently.<ref name="Telegraph I" /><ref name="Telegraph II">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3535668/Britain-unprepared-for-Mumbai-style-attack-former-head-of-SAS-says.html|title=Britain unprepared for Mumbai-style attack|last=Rayment|first=Sean|date=29 November 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref>

In April 2014, he was appointed to lead an investigation into [[Operation Trojan Horse]], an alleged plot by [[Islamists]] to take over schools in Birmingham. Due to his background in counter-terrorism, Clarke's appointment was criticised by some, including local MP [[Khalid Mahmood]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Trojan Horse probe headed by ex-Met chief Peter Clarke|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-27031941|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=15 April 2014|date=15 April 2014}}</ref>

==Honours==
On 6 March 2001, Clarke was appointed [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56145|startpage=3093|date=13 March 2001|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref> he was awarded the [[Queen's Police Medal]] in the 2003 [[Queen's Birthday Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56963|supp=yes|startpage=27|date=14 June 2003|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref> and appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the [[2006 New Year Honours]] for his work on July 2005 bombings.<ref name="BBC I">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/4569978.stm|title=7 July workers honoured by Queen|date=31 December 2005|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57855|supp=yes|startpage=10|date=31 December 2005|accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref>

